SIMPLE: alum
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Alum
<hw>Al"um</hw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>alum</ets>,
<ets>alom</ets>, OF. <ets>alum</ets>, F. <ets>alun</ets>, fr. L.
<ets>alumen</ets> alum.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A double sulphate
formed of aluminium and some other element (esp. an alkali metal) or of
aluminium. It has twenty-four molecules of water of
crystallization.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ Common <xex>alum</xex> is the double sulphate of
aluminium and potassium. It is white, transparent, very astringent, and
crystallizes easily in octahedrons. The term is extended so as to
include other double sulphates similar to alum in formula.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Alum</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Alum
<hw>Al"um</hw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To steep in, or
otherwise impregnate with, a solution of alum; to treat with alum.</def>
<rj><au>Ure.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Alumen</ent>⟦br⟧
